# 30-day work and value audit

>> Overview <<

Across the **19 shared conversations plus this audit**, central estimate:

  * **367 user prompts**, with a reasonable range of **292–454** in-total prompts
  * **291 major deliverable units**: substantial features, fixes, subsystems, release tools, test suites, or documentation packages
  * Approximately **948 hours of conventional replacement labor**
  * Approximately **$52,970 in wage-equivalent replacement value**
  * Plausible range: **750–1,150 hours** and roughly **$42,000–$64,000**
  * Actual ChatGPT subscription expense: approximately **$20**
  * Effective subscription cost: **5.45¢ per prompt**
  * Effective subscription cost: **6.87¢ per major deliverable**
  * Replacement-value-to-subscription ratio: approximately **2,649:1**

    The **948 hours are not literal elapsed hours spent during the month**. They represent how long a conventional mixture of developers, QA testers, release engineers, and technical writers might take to reproduce the delivered work. Lower-confidence estimate is roughly **140–230 active hours**, centered around **185 hours**, including prompting, local testing, copying patches, troubleshooting, reviewing output, and uploading releases.


>> Important Notes <<

  ChatGPT shared links normally contain a snapshot of a conversation through the point at which it was shared. The underlying artifacts substantiate that these were not merely plans. 

    * CryptoChess has extensive randomized, security, GUI, recovery, and release-candidate test records, as well as a finished multi-container release and operator workflow.   
    * Bitninja includes service modes, audio lip assist, eye tracking, presets, launcher work, release documentation, doctors, and GitHub packaging.  
    * Deck Card Widget includes separate controller/output windows, storage formats, editable display content, image/text layers, OBS support, and cross-platform setup documentation.  
    * SWAR and Streamer Board Console also have concrete automated and local acceptance suites.  



>> Per-app work, prompt use, time, and cost <<

  “Major units” deliberately do not count every button, field, test assertion, or minor style adjustment separately. One unit represents a meaningful feature, subsystem, repair, release tool, validation suite, or complete documentation deliverable.

